			<tr>
				<td colspan="2" height="100%" valign="top"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>vovka wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">So Lord of the Rings isn't fantasy because it features fighting? 
<br />

<br />
Strategic and Fantasy are not mutually exclusive. What the hell are you talking about?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I think the point Sonkun is trying to make is that the MMORPG 'culture' derives a large portion of its fanbase from the High Fantasy / Tolkien / D&amp;D realms.   (This isn't to say CoH / EVE online / etc. aren't good, just talking in majority, generalistic terms)
<br />

<br />
A staple of the High Fantasy / D&amp;D RPG is a party/group of 'adventurers' going out to 'slay the dragon' or 'rescue the princess' - not to 'bring the flag back to our base 3 times'   People play RPGs, and MMORPGs (and when I say people, of course I mean me) to play a Role.  To be in the Fantasy.   When I play TFC / Quake / CS, I don't play to be in a Fantasy, heck, I don't even have any attachment to my 'character' - I'm just a guy running around shooting people, playing a video game...
<br />

<br />
I think that's the part that gets me --  when I was raiding in EQ, I felt 'in the Fantasy', lots of people working together to kill dragons, or huge snakes, or gods.   I don't play a MMORPG to 'protect a flagcarrier' or to be a 'Grunt on the frontline' of some war. 
<br />

<br />
So, WoW PvP, even with it's ludicrously great rewards - breaks my 'suspension of disbelief'.   Well, not that it is that high in WoW anyway, but ... yah.</span><br /><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
